<p>In a responsible democracy, citizens, including the press, have an obligation to discuss the impact of major events as to what their meaning is and to what potential policy issues this raises.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, our public dialogue has gone out of control. But that doesn't mean discussion should be suppressed.</p>
<p>Let's go back to 9/11 - Bush/Cheney and their cohorts quickly hijacked the discussion, and more importantly were making plans out of public view. According to what I understand your POV is, Dems were right to be 100% supportive and not raise key issues about the government's performance and what actions should be taken because it would have politicized things.</p>
<p>And as to the specific crime and the response - of course it's valid to discuss whether the shelter-in-place plan was appropriate, whether releasing the pictures (which remember led to the death of the policeman) was the right procedure, how the suspect should be tried - all these things are reasonable topics for public debate and discussion. It's not per se politicizing things, it's part of being an open democracy.</p>

