<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1203537/49975923#c148?mode=alone;showrate=1#c148">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>This whole business about not reading him his rights is bullshit. &nbsp;They have enough on him to send him up for life; in the Federal case, they have enough to execute him. &nbsp;And unlike Timothy McVeigh, he won't have the full weight of the right wing legal establishment defending him. &nbsp;(And if he's part of some broader conspiracy, which is unlikely, that death penalty threat can be used to get him to reveal it.)</p>
<p>The first question is why this isn't treated as domestic terrorism? &nbsp;The older brother's rantings could, if you substitute "Jesus" for "Allah", be from any group of social conservatives in America. &nbsp;The guns and explosives were procured domestically, even though the older brother had an outstanding domestic violence conviction, which should have automatically disqualified him from possessing firearms or the sorts of gunpowder and smokeless powder that reloaders are allowed to buy. &nbsp;At the end of the day, where's the foreign connection? &nbsp;How do we know this wasn't connected to domestic right wingers? &nbsp;Other than the older brother's social media postings containing "Allah" and "Muslim", this whole event follows closely the scenario for domestic terrorism -- and because the perps are Caucasian, they are likely to receive such support.</p>
<p>In the meantime, Lindsay Graham, whose own loyalty to the United States is highly suspect in my mind (his religious fundamentalism, his support for Confederate ideology, his support for right wing domestic terrorism, his racism) has no business commenting on any of this.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:23133">liberaldregs</a> on <a href="/comments/1203537/49975923#c148">Sat Apr 20, 2013 at 07:08:07 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
